Added six-sided wood blocks, which look similar to logs, but they have the wood's "bark" texture (side texture when placed vertically) on all 6 sides.
Wood has an item form, obtainable only through commands or external tools. When placed, it acts like a normal log.
Added two new types of wood: acacia and dark oak.
The texture of acacia wood has been drastically changed, and dark oak has a unique texture.
Wood block models are now missing.

minecraft:log2 blocks with numerical metadata variants 2-3, 6-7, 10-11 and 14-15, which are inaccessible through normal gameplay, now have no model rather than appearing identical to either acacia or dark oak logs.
Wood blocks now have models again.

minecraft:log2 with metadata values 2-3, 6-7, 10-11 and 14-15 have now been completely removed from the game.
The different variant block states and the axis=none block state for both the log and log2 IDs have been split up into their own IDs.
The item form for wood blocks has been re-added.
Wood can now be obtained in the inventory.
The name of "Wood" has been changed to "Bark".
Prior to The Flattening, these blocks' numeral IDs were 17 and 162.
A crafting recipe for bark has been added.
Bark blocks can now be rotated.
Added top textures of the bark blocks.
The textures of bark have been changed back to how they were before 1.13-pre1.
Bark blocks have been changed back to <type> Wood.
Bark IDs have been changed to <type>_wood.
The textures of wood have been changed.
The textures of wood except jungle wood have been changed.
Wood and stripped wood can now be used to craft campfires.
Stripped wood can now be crafted from stripped logs.
Added regular and stripped crimson and warped hyphae.
Corridors in mineshafts now generate with wooden pillars for support if needed.
Oak wood can no longer generate in mineshafts.
Added regular and stripped mangrove wood.
Bark blocks can be obtained only using world editing.
Added jungle, acacia, and dark oak variants for bark blocks.
Due to the addition of commands, bark blocks can now be placed using /setblock ~ ~ ~ log 12, without the need for an inventory editor.
Added stripped bark as part of Experimental Gameplay.
Stripped bark can be placed only with /setblock ~ ~ ~ stripped_<type>_log 3.
Bark is now called "<type> Wood" and "Stripped <type> Wood".
Wood now exists as a separate block; previously placed wood looks the same, but still drops logs instead of wood.
The textures of wood have been changed.
A crafting recipe for wood has been added.
Wood blocks and stripped wood have been added to the creative inventory.
Wood and stripped wood now generate in the new villages.
Wood and stripped wood is now used to craft campfires and smokers.
Added crimson and warped hyphae, including stripped variants. Their appearances are completely unknown.
Added regular and stripped mangrove wood.
Added oak, spruce, birch and jungle oak bark blocks. They can be obtained only by world editing.
Added acacia and dark oak bark blocks. They can be obtained only by world editing.
Added stripped bark. They can be obtained only by world editing.
Bark and stripped bark is now called "<type> Wood" and "Stripped <type> Wood".
Wood and stripped wood can now be obtained in the creative inventory or through crafting.
The textures of wood have been changed.
Wood can now be used to craft planks.

texts.text: This article is about the bark block. For the block found in trees formerly named "wood", see Log. For other uses, see Wood (disambiguation).
Wood or hyphae is a block that has the log's "bark" texture on all six sides. It comes in 9 types: oak, spruce, birch, jungle, acacia, dark oak, crimson, warped, and mangrove.
Stripped wood or stripped hyphae is a variant obtained when any axe is used on wood or hyphae respectively.

Wood and hyphae can be broken by hand, but using an axe speeds up the process.
Times are for unenchanted tools as wielded by players with no status effects, measured in seconds. For more information, see Breaking § Speed.
Oak wood and stripped oak wood generate in plains villages.
Acacia wood generate in savanna villages.
Spruce wood and stripped spruce wood generate in snowy plains, snowy taiga and taiga villages.
Wood or hyphae can be crafted out of four matching logs or stems, yielding three wood or hyphae as a result.
Using an axe on wood or hyphae turns it into stripped wood or hyphae, which act the same as regular wood or hyphae.
Wood or hyphae can be used as a decorative block in place of normal logs or stems.
Wood and stripped wood can be used as a fuel in furnaces, smelting 1.5 items per block.
Hyphae and stripped hyphae cannot be used as a fuel in furnaces.
Cocoa beans can be placed on the side of both jungle logs and stripped jungle logs to grow new cocoa pods.
Wood and hyphae can be placed under note blocks to produce "bass" sounds.

In real life, hyphae are branching filaments that collectively make real-life mycelium.[1]
The word "hyphae" is actually plural, the singular form is "hypha."
